<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911029-0115</DOCNO><DOCID>911029-0115.</DOCID><HL>   Dividend News:   Kollmorgen Reports   Third-Quarter Loss;   Restructuring Cited</HL><DATE>10/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   KOL</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)DIVIDENDS (DIV)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><NS>DIVIDENDS (DIV)EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   SIMSBURY, Conn. -- Kollmorgen Corp. reported a $26 millionthird-quarter loss, which reflected restructuring charges,and slashed its quarterly dividend 75%.   The motors, controls and electro-optical instrumentscompany reduced its dividend to two cents quarterly fromeight cents, payable Dec. 4 to shares of record Nov. 22. Thereduction saves about $577,000 quarterly.</LP><TEXT>   The quarterly loss, equal to $2.77 a share, compares withyear-earlier net income of $837,000, or three cents a share,which included a $908,000 loss from discontinued operations.Sales fell 16% to $46.9 million.   The quarterly loss reflects $23 million of one-timecharges, including $11.4 million for work-force reductions,$6.2 million for a nonrecurring operating loss because ofunanticipated costs on several fixed-priced militarycontracts in the electro-optical division, and $5.4 millionin write-downs for inventories.   The company said that it will have cut the number ofemployees by 475, or 19%, by year-end, compared with lastDec. 31; corporate expenses, it added, will have been reducedby 30%.   Without the one-time charges, the company would have had a$3 million net loss for the quarter, mainly because ofresults at the electro-optical instruments segment.   Chairman George P. Stephen said that although the companydoesn't see any significant improvements in revenue duringthe fourth quarter, the company hopes to return toprofitability in 1992.</TEXT></DOC>